War Is Starting to Pressure Housing in Portugal — And Construction Is Already Feeling It

Portugal’s housing market entered 2026 with the same structural imbalance that has defined the last decade: demand remains resilient, supply remains constrained, and prices continue to climb faster than affordability can sustain. But in recent weeks, a new pressure point has started to emerge — geopolitics.

The escalation of conflict in the Middle East is beginning to ripple through the Portuguese residential market, not through sentiment alone, but through something much more immediate: energy, logistics, and construction costs. What initially looked like a distant geopolitical shock is now becoming a practical concern for developers, contractors, and ultimately homebuyers.

And while it is still too early to call this a structural shift, the first effects are already visible.

Construction Is Already Feeling the Pressure

The most immediate transmission mechanism is energy.

As fuel prices rise, the impact is felt across the entire construction value chain — from raw material transport and machinery operations to industrial production and site logistics. Construction is particularly exposed because it remains one of the most energy-sensitive sectors in the economy.

This is where geopolitical instability begins to matter for housing.

Rising fuel costs do not only increase transportation expenses. They also push up manufacturing costs for materials, create uncertainty in supplier pricing, and indirectly raise wage pressure through higher living costs. In practical terms, this means developers are now facing a more volatile cost base at a time when margins are already under pressure.

That volatility is no longer theoretical. Some suppliers in Portugal have already started delaying quotations due to uncertainty around short-term pricing, especially in materials and logistics-sensitive categories. That is typically one of the earliest signs of cost stress entering the construction cycle.

Portugal was already seeing upward pressure in construction costs before the latest geopolitical escalation. According to INE, Portugal’s New Housing Construction Cost Index rose 4.0% in 2025, with labour costs increasing 7.7%, reinforcing how exposed the sector already was even before the recent energy shock.

In that context, external shocks do not create the problem — they amplify it.

Portugal’s Housing Market Was Already Fragile

The reason this matters so much is simple: Portugal’s housing market was already operating with very little room for additional cost pressure.

The country continues to face a structural supply deficit built over more than a decade of underbuilding. At the start of the century, Portugal was licensing over 100,000 homes per year. That collapsed after 2008 and never recovered at the pace required to meet accumulated demand.

Even though construction activity has improved, the market remains structurally undersupplied.

This is the central issue in Portuguese housing today. Prices are not being driven by one isolated factor. They are being sustained by a long-term mismatch between supply and demand, compounded by slow licensing, labour shortages, legal uncertainty, and rising construction costs.

The OECD recently reinforced this point, highlighting weak housing investment, labour shortages in construction, and long permitting delays as some of the main structural barriers to increasing supply in Portugal.

That means the market was already vulnerable before geopolitical instability entered the equation.

Why This Matters for House Prices

In the short term, housing prices in Portugal are unlikely to fall.

That remains the baseline.

Demand is still strong, particularly in urban and peri-urban markets such as Lisbon, Porto, and Vila Nova de Gaia. Supply remains constrained. Financing conditions have stabilised. And the structural shortage of quality housing remains unresolved.

This is why most market participants still expect price resilience in the near term.

Fitch recently projected another 15% increase in Portuguese house prices in 2026, following an already exceptional rise in 2025, citing exactly the same drivers: limited supply and sustained domestic and international demand.

But if the conflict in the Middle East persists and energy prices remain elevated, the risk is no longer just price resilience — it is renewed price acceleration.

Not because demand is suddenly stronger, but because replacement cost may rise again.

That is the key distinction.

In a supply-constrained market, when construction costs rise, developers rarely absorb the full increase. Over time, those costs are repriced into the market, particularly in new-build residential. That tends to feed directly into higher asking prices, especially in mid-market and upper-mid-market urban product where margins are tighter and replacement cost discipline is stronger.

In other words: if construction becomes more expensive, housing usually follows.

The Government Is Trying to Help — But Execution Still Matters

Portugal’s policy response is directionally correct, but still incomplete.

Measures such as reduced VAT on construction (6%) and licensing simplification are broadly positive in theory, particularly in a market where viability is increasingly constrained by cost and bureaucracy.

But execution remains the real test.

The VAT measure, while attractive on paper, still creates liquidity pressure for developers because the cost is incurred during construction while the benefit is largely recovered only at the end of the process. In practice, that weakens its immediate impact on project viability.

Licensing reform is potentially more important.

Permitting delays remain one of the biggest bottlenecks in Portuguese residential development. When approvals take two to three years, capital becomes less efficient, risk increases, and project pipelines slow down. That directly reduces supply responsiveness.

So while fiscal incentives may help at the margin, permitting reform remains the most critical lever if Portugal wants to improve housing delivery at scale.

The Core Problem Has Not Changed

The Middle East conflict is not the root cause of Portugal’s housing crisis.

But it may become the next accelerant.

Portugal’s housing market was already dealing with structural undersupply, slow licensing, rising labour costs, and persistent affordability pressure. What geopolitical instability does is add another layer of cost volatility into an already constrained system.

That matters because housing markets do not need a demand shock to reprice.

Sometimes, all they need is a cost shock in a market where supply is already too tight.

And that is precisely where Portugal stands today.

Sources: idealista/news, INE, OECD, Fitch Ratings.